# Backend — Spring Boot / Java / Maven Conventions

## Modules
- Maven multi-module under `backend/`: parent `pom.xml` (`aiplane-backend`, groupId
  `dev.madmmas.aiplane`) manages the Spring Boot 3.4.x / Spring Cloud 2024.0.x / Spring AI
  1.0.0 BOMs via `dependencyManagement`. Two modules today: `api-server` (port 8080, the
  modular monolith) and `config-server` (port 8888, Spring Cloud Config Server).
- New backend capability belongs in `api-server` unless it's genuinely a separate
  deployable service — don't add a third Maven module without checking it against
  `docs/SPEC.md` §3 first.
- Shared plugin versions (compiler, surefire, failsafe, spring-boot-maven-plugin) live in
  the parent's `pluginManagement` — set versions there, not per-module.

## Package structure (modular monolith)
- Domain packages under `dev.madmmas.aimanager.*`: `prompt`, `guardrail`, `user`,
  `provider`, `usage`, `security`, `project`. Each currently exists only as an empty
  `package-info.java` — when adding real classes, keep each domain self-contained
  (controller/service/repository/dto together) and don't reach into another domain's
  package directly; go through its service interface instead.
- `common/` is cross-cutting only: `common.config`, `common.dto`, `common.exception`,
  `common.util`. Don't put domain-specific DTOs in `common.dto` — only genuinely shared
  shapes (e.g. a generic error response envelope) belong there.
- **Known quirk — don't "fix" it in passing:** the Java package root is still
  `dev.madmmas.aimanager` (the pre-rebrand product name), while the Maven `groupId` is
  already `dev.madmmas.aiplane` and everything else in the repo says "AIPlane". A full
  package rename touches every source file, the logging config in `application.yml`, and
  both Dockerfiles — it needs its own dedicated issue/PR, not a drive-by rename inside an
  unrelated feature change.

## Persistence — hybrid (JPA for prompts, JdbcTemplate elsewhere)
- Prompt domain uses `spring-boot-starter-data-jpa` with
  `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=validate` (Flyway owns schema). Entities live under
  `dev.madmmas.aimanager.prompt`.
- Project and guardrail still use `JdbcTemplate` / Spring JDBC — do not rewrite them
  opportunistically inside an unrelated PR; migrate when those packages need a substantial
  change.
- Prefer JPA for new domains that map cleanly to SPEC entities. Keep JDBC when a package
  already ships working repositories and the change is not about persistence style.

## Flyway migrations
- Versioned migrations live in `backend/api-server/src/main/resources/db/migration/`,
  named `V<N>__<snake_case_description>.sql` (V1-V9 already cover projects, prompts,
  prompt_versions, guardrails, guardrail_sets, users, api_keys, usage_events,
  config_properties). Never edit an already-applied `V<N>` file — add a new `V<N+1>`.
- Local dev seed data is a **repeatable** migration (`R__01_seed_local_dev.sql`) under
  `db/seed/`, kept separate from versioned migrations on purpose — never move seed data
  into a `V*` file, or it'll be treated as required schema and applied everywhere.
- `application.yml` sets `baseline-on-migrate: true` and
  `locations: classpath:db/migration,classpath:db/seed` — don't introduce a third
  migration location without updating that config to match.

## Spring AI / Config Server
- Provider integration (Anthropic, OpenAI, etc.) goes through Spring AI's `ChatClient`
  abstraction inside the `provider` package — don't call a provider's HTTP API directly
  from a domain service; that defeats the provider-agnostic principle in SPEC §1.
- Config Server runs in `native` profile today, serving `classpath:/config`
  (`backend/config-server/src/main/resources/config/application.yml`, explicitly marked
  as a Phase 5 placeholder). Don't wire real prompt/guardrail payloads into that file —
  that's the JDBC backend + `PromptConfigExporter` work, which is scoped Phase 5.

## Lombok
- Lombok is on the classpath (`optional` dependency) — prefer it for boilerplate
  (`@Getter`, `@Builder`, `@RequiredArgsConstructor` for constructor injection) over
  hand-written getters/setters and field injection.
- Avoid `@Data` on any future JPA entity — it generates `equals`/`hashCode` over every
  field, which breaks predictably once lazy-loaded associations are involved.

## Style
- No Java-specific formatter (Checkstyle/Spotless/google-java-format) is configured —
  `.editorconfig`'s generic `[*]` rule (2-space indent, LF, UTF-8) is the only enforced
  convention, and the existing Java code already follows it. Match that until a real
  Java formatter is added.

## Local dev / Docker gotcha
- `api-server/pom.xml`'s `maven-surefire-plugin` config pins `DOCKER_API_VERSION=1.44`
  because docker-java's default (API 1.24) gets rejected by Docker Engine 25+/Docker
  Desktop. If a Testcontainers-based test fails locally with a Docker API version
  mismatch, check this setting before assuming your local Docker install is broken.
